    "method": {
      "description": "Longitudinal survey study of 229 preschool teachers measuring weekend recovery experiences (relaxation, mastery, control, psychological detachment) and non-work hassles, and their associations with discrete affective states at the end of the weekend and after the following workweek. The study employed confirmatory factor analyses to validate affect structure and hierarchical regression analyses controlling for demographics and prior affect.",
      "steps": [
        "Recruit preschool teachers and collect demographics.",
        "Administer surveys at Time 1 (Friday after work) to assess baseline affective states and demographics.",
        "Administer surveys at Time 2 (Sunday night) to assess weekend recovery experiences, non-work hassles, and affective states.",
        "Administer surveys at Time 3 (following Friday after work) to assess affective states during the workweek.",
        "Compute scale scores for recovery experiences (relaxation, mastery, control, detachment), non-work hassles, and PANAS-X affective states (joviality, serenity, self-assurance, fear, hostility, sadness, fatigue).",
        "Conduct confirmatory factor analyses to compare a seven-factor affect model with a two-factor model across time points.",
        "Run hierarchical regression analyses predicting Time 2 and Time 3 affective states from weekend recovery experiences and hassles, controlling for demographics and prior (Time 1) affect.",
        "Interpret coefficients, significance levels, and variance explained to evaluate hypotheses."
      ],
      "models": "Confirmatory factor analysis (model comparison: seven-factor vs. two-factor); hierarchical multiple regression controlling for demographics and prior affect.",
      "outcome_variable": "Affective states measured via PANAS-X: positive (joviality, serenity, self-assurance) and negative (fear, hostility, sadness, fatigue).",
      "independent_variables": "Weekend recovery experiences (relaxation, mastery, control, psychological detachment) and non-work hassles.",
      "control_variables": "Demographic variables and prior levels of affective states.",
      "tools_software": "not stated"
    },
    "results": {
      "summary": "Weekend recovery experiences were significantly related to affective states, with stronger effects at the end of the weekend than after the following workweek. Relaxation and mastery were positively associated with positive affective states; psychological detachment was positively related to positive affect and negatively related to negative affect. Non-work hassles were positively related to negative affective states. Control over non-work time did not significantly predict positive affect when other variables were included.",
